      <body>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e65"
            >A. Plant medicines</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e69"
             subtype="h2">1. Diseases in the head area</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e73"
             subtype="h3">[Jeannie Gibson]</head>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e78">
            <form>
               <orth>cairt a’ chaineil</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Mint tea. Disease: headache (ceann goirt). Part used: leaf and stem. How prepared: boiled. Sources of information: aunt.</def>
         </entry>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e86"
             subtype="h3">[Christina MacGillivray]</head>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e91">
            <form>
               <orth>fuaran tuirneip</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Turnip poultice. Disease: abscess.</def>
         </entry>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e99"
             subtype="h2">2. Respiratory diseases</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e103"
             subtype="h3">[Jeannie Gibson]</head>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e108">
            <form>
               <orth>fuaran-sgeallain</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Wild mustard poultice. Disease: pneumonia, colds, pl [sic] [pleurisy?]. Part used: leaves and stems. How prepared: mixed with hot water to form a kind of paste, and then put between
        two cloths. Can also simply use cold mustard leaves and stems in a bandage (bànn-arad).</def>
         </entry>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e116"
             subtype="h2">3. The blood</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e120"
             subtype="h3">[Jeannie Gibson]</head>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e125">
            <form>
               <orth>cama-mhil</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Camomile. Disease: chilblains (millicheartain). Part used: roots and flower and stem. How prepared: boiled to form camomile lotion (ola-cama-mhil). Lotion just rubbed on, not
        covered.</def>
         </entry>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e133"
             subtype="h3">[Christina MacGillivray]</head>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e138">
            <form>
               <orth>lìon an damhain allaidh</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Spider’s web. Disease: cuts, wounds.</def>
         </entry>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e146"
             subtype="h2">4. The bowels and stomach</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e150"
             subtype="h3">[Angus Henderson, blacksmith (retired), Tobermory (79)]</head>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e155">
            <form>
               <orth>cuach Phàraig</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Greater plantain. Disease: piles. How prepared: whole plant (including roots) boiled in water until very little water left. Butter then mixed with finely ground oatmeal. Formed an
        ointment.</def>
         </entry>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e163"
             subtype="h2">5. Bladder and kidneys</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e167"
             subtype="h2">6. Other internal organs</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e171"
             subtype="h2">7. Gynaecological complaints</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e175"
             subtype="h2">8. Skin diseases not already mentioned</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e179"
             subtype="h3">[Jeannie Gibson]</head>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e184">
            <form>
               <orth>a’ chopag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Docken. Disease: burns. Parts used: leaves. How prepared: leaf put against burn with bandage.</def>
         </entry>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e192"
             subtype="h3">[Christina MacGillivray]</head>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e197">
            <form>
               <orth>rusg buidhe nan creag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Yellow lichen on rocks by shore. Disease: burns. How prepared: lichen boiled until nearly dry, then mixed with fresh butter to make an ointment.</def>
         </entry>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e205"
             subtype="h2">9. Acute diseases</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e209"
             subtype="h2">10. The skeleton and muscles</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e213"
            >B. Treatments which did not involve the use of plants</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e217"
            >C. Veterinary medicine</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e221"
             subtype="h3">[Jeannie Gibson]</head>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e226">
            <form>
               <orth>seannas</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Like honeysuckle. For constipation in cattle and other stomach upsets. Leaves and roots boiled and then strained.</def>
         </entry>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e234"
             subtype="h3">[John Campbell (Teonaidh Chailein), Taoslainn, Buneasain]</head>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e239">
            <form>
               <orth>mart trì foil</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Bog bean. Cattle – constipation. Boiled and then strained. Known as ‘tribhealach’ (also taken as tonic by people when mixed with lucozade and/or shandy, etc.)</def>
         </entry>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e247"
            >D. What do you think is the English name for the plants called in Gaelic:</head>
         <head
             xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e251"
             subtype="h3">[Jeannie Gibson]</head>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e256">
            <form>
               <orth>móthan</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Ladynut. ‘Braonan’ in Mull. (Used to eat them.)</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e265">
            <form>
               <orth>[braonan]</orth>
               <pron>[See móthan]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[See móthan]</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="TireeandMull_MullJGibsonetalmedplants-d0e274">
            <form>
               <orth>cairmeal, carra-meille</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Camomile.</def>
         </entry>
